56. Avoid duplicate font calls (BEG, MED)
Total rookie mistake and one I see happening all the time. The theme calls a webfont (letâ€™s say Googleâ€™s Montserrat), the pagebuilder calls the exact same one, and the pop-up plugin calls it one more time. So now, we got 3 calls and 30 requests to Googleâ€™s webfont servers to download the same damn font multiple times. How stupid!
Try to load fonts only from one place, preferably your theme.All other font-settings places (like plugins) should use the â€œinheritâ€ option instead of picking a font.Watch out for plugins that let you select fonts (pagebuilder, slider, pop-up, mega-menu).
The common mistake is that users think they have to re-select their font in every website setting. Donâ€™t do that!
6. Caching optimization
Caching is best defined as saving the processed requests so they can be served faster when requested again. Itâ€™s used in every aspect of computer technology since forever, and absolutely essential for speeding up your page load.
There are many kinds of caching (across different layers, protocols, and services) and many ways to configure them. Set them up right and youâ€™ll have a fast site that reduces server load and saves money. Set them up wrong and you have a site thatâ€™s sometimes-fast and or has broken design and functions.
If youâ€™ve ever heard of people complaining about cache, itâ€™s a combination of them not knowing how to configure for their use case and/or using a caching solution configured for server-efficiency more so than speed.
57. Choosing the right server for caching (BEG-ADV, HIGH)
Full-page caching (aka â€œstatic cachingâ€ or just â€œcachingâ€) means to prebuild the entire page, making it static like HTML so itâ€™s ready to serve immediately when the page is visited. There is no wait for any database queries or PHP processingâ€¦the page simply appears instantly. Like a burger that was made before you order it!
Back in the days, caching was only done by the web server (therefore called â€œserver cachingâ€) and utilized to keep server load down. It was a tactic to help busy web servers handle lots of traffic. Somebody later realized it could help speed up todayâ€™s bloated sites so now, caching is also used from a speed point-of-view and deployed even on small webservers with little traffic.
Developers even created software-level caching mechanisms to recreate the same benefit for users without server access, or on servers without â€œserver-cachingâ€ modules enabled. Of course, theyâ€™re not as fast as true server-caching but still massively impactful and in some cases even more useful because of having extra caching features.
The most important distinction for regular users is to know their caching limitations with each webhost or web-server. In terms of webserverâ€¦Apache, LiteSpeed, and NGINX all have different server-caching available.
In terms of webhostingâ€¦just know that some webhosts allow you the freedom to use their server-caching or any 3rd-party plugin of your choice. Other webhosts force you to use their proprietary caching solution. Of course, they will sell it as being high-tech and â€œbest performanceâ€ but usually itâ€™s a stripped-down caching solution thatâ€™s built for resource-efficiency rather than aggressive performance. If you try to use an outside plugin, it simply wonâ€™t work or the webhosting company will automatically disable it.
Caching is usually faster and more resource-efficient from the server rather than through software-level PHP caching.If using LiteSpeed server, you can use built-in LiteSpeed server caching.If using NGINX server, you can use built-in FastCGI server caching.If using Apache (which you shouldnâ€™t), you can use Varnish proxy or even NGINX proxy.All web-servers can use any software-level php caching (via cache plugin). But some plugins are designed more for Apache/LiteSpeed servers, others for NGINX servers.Careful of certain webhosts (especially â€œmanaged webhostsâ€) who force you to use their caching solutions and wonâ€™t let you use other cache plugins.
Just know that the webserver or webhosting company you choose will affect your caching experience and what caching plugins you can use.
58. Choosing the right cache plugins (BEG-ADV, HIGH)
Iâ€™ve tried over 50 different cache plugins. The best ones have useful features, easy-to-use, and donâ€™t break your site. If you manage only a few sites, you might prefer aggressive plugins with many optimizations and even Facebook groups where people share tricks. If you manage dozens of clients, youâ€™ll prefer a safer plugin with less features and less chance of issues.
Best all-around cache plugins (allowed on any webserver) are Swift Performance or WP Rocket. Swift more aggressive, Rocket more stable.There are other good cache plugins as well (WP Fastest Cache, Breeze, WP Performance, Comet Cache, Borlabs).W3TC sucks and very difficult to configure. Donâ€™t use unless youâ€™re a pro.If using LiteSpeed server, you can use LiteSpeed Cache plugin. My favorite.If using NGINX server, you can stick with NGINX helper plugins to keep it simple or a full-featured cache plugin like (Swift or WP Rocket).Do not combine multiple cache plugins!I donâ€™t like combining cache plugins with other performance plugins either, but it can work if configured carefully (and not overlapping functions).
Deciding which cache plugin to use depends on your use case.
Small site with 400 pages and little traffic? â€“ Swift or WP Rocket, with precaching enabled.Medium site with 400-1k pages, and medium traffic? â€“ Can go with cache plugin Swift/Rocket or server caching LiteSpeed/NGINX. Both have pros and cons.Big site with 1k or more pages and lots of traffic? â€“ I like custom-configured LiteSpeed Cache or native-NGINX cache and no precaching necessary since you have so much traffic.
59. Cache plugin configuration (INT-ADV, HIGH)
Cache plugins are more complicated than ever to configure now since they do so many more things than just caching. This section covers specifically only caching-related settings. Regarding other options you see in cache plugin settings, my recommendation will be in other parts of this guide.
Rewrites vs PHP â€“ most cache plugins only give you the PHP option. If you have the option to use the rewrite method, try that as itâ€™s faster. If it causes problems, then switch to php method.Cache TTL â€“ this means how long the cache should last for. You should set this about as long as your content update intervals. If you update every day, then set 24 hours. If you almost never update, can make it 1 month.Private cache or logged-in users/pages â€“ donâ€™t use unless you really have that many logged-in users and you know how to prevent cache from mixing up content between users.Separate mobile cache â€“ donâ€™t use unless you have AMP or a specific design or content that only shows up on mobile. Just because you have a mobile-responsive site doesnâ€™t mean you need this.Caching 404 pages â€“ yes if you have many users hitting them. Better if you redirect all of them to actual pages.Dynamic cache â€“ great for caching urls with queries or filters, like searches or ecommerce product filters.Exclude â€“ absolutely critical for excluding pages that shouldnâ€™t be cached. I typically exclude checkout, logged-in user pages, or pages with forms.Browser cache â€“ yes, enable it.Heartbeat control â€“ I usually disable for all pages except posts. Or if you need it on, you can increase its interval to every 120 seconds.
Not every caching setup or cache plugin will allow you to configure all those options. Donâ€™t freak out if you donâ€™t see them. In fact, there are so many possible settingsâ€¦plese refer to my cache configuration guides below:
Swift Performance cache setup guideWP Rocket cache setup guideLiteSpeed cache setup guideFor all other cache plugins, I think you can follow my guides above to get a general idea.
60. Configuring cache-prebuild (INT, MED-HIGH)
One of the most overlooked aspects of caching for me is the cache-prebuild process. Some plugins call it â€œcache-preloadâ€, others call it â€œcache-warmingâ€ or â€œcache-crawlerâ€. The cache-prebuild function is a mechanism that pre-caches pages so they load quickly when visited. Back in the old days, caching was only used on high traffic sites and so no cache-preload was necessary. The cache was built by the first visitor and all subsequent visitors benefitted from an already-built cache. This was fine since you had thousands of visits and only the very first person was unlucky to see a â€œslowerâ€ page.
But in todayâ€™s caching era, letting the â€œfirst person warm your cacheâ€ is a terrible idea if you have very little traffic. On a not-so-busy site with no cache prebuild, it might seem like all your visitors hit a cold (uncached) page. FYI: users hitting cold cache will see a slower page load than without any caching at all!
So anyway, we have cache-prebuilding now. There are very few servers that have or allow a server-wide cache prebuild function. Theyâ€™re probably afraid of users abusing it. Itâ€™s in the same logic that many webhosts wonâ€™t allow you to use those broken-link checker plugins (because it eats up precious resources).
LiteSpeed servers have a built-in cache crawl function. Few webhosts allow it on shared servers though. Youâ€™ll probably only get access if you have it on your own VPS.Anybody not on LiteSpeedâ€¦.well, there are many server-level cache warming mechanism and scripts out there but not quite so user-friendly. You can search them out if you insist. Itâ€™s much easier if youâ€™re on LiteSpeed, though.The best server caching script I found is OCP. Read my OCP guide.The only option (for most people) is to use a cache plugin that has cache prebuild functions built-in like Swift Performance and now WP Rocket (which copied that idea from Swift).Prebuilding improves the caching experience on your site by a whole lot. Enable it if you can!
There are a few instances where you SHOULD NOT use cache-prebuild. One is if you have many visitors, itâ€™s useless since thereâ€™s already live traffic warming the cache. The other is when you have too many pages.
I would say 1k pages is the general threshold. If you have over 1k pages and you update your site often, I recommend NOT pre-caching since your server will use many resources and never even finish the job. If your cache gets purged before it ever finishes, itâ€™s stuck in a perpetual cycle of constantly prebuilding cache thatâ€™s never used.
61. Object caching configuration (BEG-INT, MED-HIGH)
Object caching is useful for dynamic sites (constantly-refreshed data and/or canâ€™t be cached) or any sites with lots of calculated numbers/reports in admin backend. Object caching saves the database calls in RAM so they donâ€™t have to be looked up every time theyâ€™re queried.
Because RAM is precious (less abundant than hard drive space and necessary for running programs), object caching is not usually allowed on many shared hosting plans. Also it has to be enabled through the serverâ€¦so itâ€™s only possible if you have your own server or on a hosting plan that allows object caching.
Object caching must be enabled from the server.Object caching can be managed through the webhosting control panel or WordPress plugin. (Plugin is better.)Itâ€™s best if you have a cache plugin that manages both page caching and object caching (like LiteSpeed Cache). This way, they purge cache at the same time.You can use an object cache expiry time of 5 to 10 minutes to be safe. But if your content isnâ€™t update often, you can go higher like up to 30-60 minutes.
I recommend not to use object caching if you have just a static site. In some cases, itâ€™s even slower than just plain page-caching. Enabling it â€œjust in caseâ€ does not help! Of course, you can test and see for yourself.
Top reasons to use object cache:
Slow admin backend.Slow database-heavy functions.Donâ€™t know if your pages are suffering from slow query? Check with Query Monitor.
62. Browser cache aka â€œhtaccess expires headersâ€ (BEG, LOW)
This is that common tactic where people paste a bunch of lines into their htaccess so static files are browser-cached for a long time (1 week, 1 month, or even a year) so users donâ€™t have re-download them again. Maybe it was a big deal beforeâ€¦well it isnâ€™t anymore.
Many devices (like mobile) have limited space and delete their browser cache when they want, not when you want.Browser cache only helps for returning visitors, and many sites donâ€™t have much repeat traffic anyway. (Besides, itâ€™s the new visitors that we care more about improving user experience.)If you want to use browser cache, itâ€™s more conveniently done through a cache pluginâ€¦rather than copy-pasting long commands into your htaccess file.
63. Ignore query strings on page caching (BEG, MED)
Query strings are (the extra text at the end of urls) used to send information to the server. Examples of query strings below and what they do:
search â€“ show different search results. (e.g. search?=wordpress+tips)ref â€“ lets the site track who referred the user and save info within conversion tracking software. (e.g. ref?=affiliateID)fbclid â€“ lets the site know the user came from Facebook. (e.g. fbclid=123ABC)(product) filter â€“ show different products based on name, price, size or other product specifications. (e.g. filter_size?=large)
As you can see, some of these query strings actually alter the page content whereas other strings show the same page content regardless of the query string. The idea here is to exclude the query strings (that donâ€™t change content) from caching so your cache mechanism doesnâ€™t store those hits as a different page. This would save your server from unnecessary work recaching the same page under a different url string AND serve the page faster to visitors from existing cache.
This makes a big difference for visitors coming in from query string urls such as Facebook ads, affiliate links, email newsletter links (with conversion-tracking).
Hereâ€™s how you IGNORE Query Strings when Caching.
64. Private caching for logged-in users (ADV, MED)
Private caching is rarely practiced as most sites donâ€™t need it (they donâ€™t have many logged-in users). Caching public pages is easy since everyone sees the same page. Caching private pages is hard because of having to cache how each user sees the page differently AND (preferably) not wasting so much space resaving mostly similar pages over and over in cache.
Some private pages are easy â€“ same content for all logged-in users, but something else for users not logged in.Some private pages are harder â€“ shows mostly same content but also custom data depending on the user (like their name/username).Other private pages are tricky â€“ shows completely different content to each user.
The easiest way to deal with private pages is to use object caching instead of page caching. To be more aggressive, you can carefully enable private cachingâ€¦BUT make sure users canâ€™t see each others info and the public canâ€™t see private content.
There are certain mechanisms out there like LiteSpeedâ€™s ESI feature where you can show different content and widgets depending on the usersâ€¦which is nice. But ultimately at this level, you need to either hire a pro or spend lots of time to configure something that not only works but also doesnâ€™t eat up so much resources (memory and space). Private caching is tough!
65. HTML-caching at the edge (INT, MED)
This is a relatively new technology for WordPress. There are several plugins and services out there that can cache your pages at the edge and use CDN mirrors to serve them to clients around the world. There are 3 main benefits:
Caching done on their server, not yours â€“ reduces your server load, helps slow webhosting, decrease server costs, allow caching even if server doesnâ€™t have it. Basicallyâ€¦allows you fast speeds even if your webhosting/server sucks!HTML delivered from CDN â€“ traditionally, CDNâ€™s only transfer static assets like images and CSS/JS. With this new edge-caching for HTML, they can serve the HTML from the nearby pop server as wellâ€¦theoretically improving page load for visitors far from your origin server.Further DDOS protection â€“ since less of your server is used, less of your server is exposed to DDOS attacks.
Notable edge-caching plugins and services available:
QUIC.cloud â€“ from the makers of LiteSpeed webservers. Their Q.C service allows any website to benefit from LiteSpeed quickness even if they donâ€™t have LiteSpeed servers.Shifter â€“ sold as a â€œstatic site generator for WordPressâ€. Seems to be a very different user experience from the usual WordPress workflow.WP Cloudflare Super Page Cache â€“ allows you to cache everything with the free Cloudflare plan. Something previous plugins have claimed to do but fail in one way or another.I believe there are some more but I canâ€™t find them now.
Do you need these services, or are they beneficial if you already have a fast server? I think not so much. I donâ€™t use any of them as Iâ€™m happy with my server caching already. But these can be great options for those on weaker servers. Keep an eye on this segment as Iâ€™m sure it will evolve quickly.
7. Local asset optimization
Assets are any static files loading from your server. CSS stylesheets, JS scripts, images, fonts, videos. They need to be processed quickly because they often ARE the content OR they directly affect how the content is shown. Simply put, your content cannot load until your assets are loaded!
Now the trick is in how we load the assets. Some should load first, others should load later. Stuff thatâ€™s visual and near the top of the page should be prioritized. What we donâ€™t want is less-important assets to block the critical ones. How else can we optimize the way they load?
66. Reduce asset requests. (BEG-ADV, HIGH)
The fastest request is the one not made! And the most obvious way to reduce asset requests (and overall HTML) is not to call them in the first place. Many people spend so much time trying to compress and combine junk that shouldnâ€™t have even been there in the first place! Please reconsider everything you have on your page.
Get rid of stuff you donâ€™t need. (Plugins, images, fonts, etc.)Get rid of visual effects you donâ€™t need. (Animations, mouseovers, etc.)Disable unnecessary plugin CSS/JS.Consider moving things to other pages. Donâ€™t put your entire site on the homepage.The less stuff you have loaded, the fewer assets needed.
And for the assets you still have? We have more tricksâ€¦
67. Remove unused WordPress core JS (BEG, LOW)
WordPress by default includes a couple javascripts that might not be used. You can disable them with some simple snippets in your functions.php file.
wp-embed.js â€“ conveniently embed Youtube videos or unfurl links in the editor and content. If you literally never embed videos and all your content is just text and images, you can dequeue it.wp-emoji-release.js â€“ little JS that turns punctuation marks into emojis. You can disable this since modern browsers already support emojis natively.jquery-migrate.min.js â€“ supports older WordPress themes and plugins still running on the old jquery library. Sites using updated themes/plugins can safely disable this.jquery.js â€“ largish JS library used by many themes/plugins. Itâ€™s convenient since themes/plugins wonâ€™t load extra JS if they can use the default jquery JS. The issue is some themes/plugins DONâ€™T use it and they load their own JS anyway. Disable if your theme/plugins donâ€™t use it. If you donâ€™t know, then disable and check everything carefullyâ€¦or consult the documentation for every theme/plugin that you installed.
Iâ€™m sure youâ€™ve seen some performance plugins that offer to disable these for you. I suggest not using them as they sometimes create their own extra load. I prefer disabling these manually in functions.php OR using the built-in functions in my caching plugin.
68. Use native CSS/JS optimizations from your theme & plugins (BEG, MED)
If your theme or plugin has built-in CSS/JS optimization features, use them as they are safer and likely wonâ€™t cause any issues.
Theme or pagebuilders allowing CSS/JS merge and minification â€“ use it.Plugins allowing different CSS generation options â€“ always pick â€œexternal CSS fileâ€, as itâ€™s faster and safer than putting them â€œinlineâ€ or in â€œdatabaseâ€. Only use inline if itâ€™s super tiny CSS (like 3 lines).
69. Combine CSS/JS for small sites only! (BEG, LOW)
There is a huge debate whether you should combine and minify your CSS/JS, aka â€œconcatenationâ€. I believe itâ€™s better (in general) if you donâ€™t combine CSS/JS . With that said, smaller sites can benefit from combining since most of the load time for tiny CSS/JS will come from the DNS lookup rather than the code processing.
As for larger sites or larger CSS files, I definitely recommend not combining them. You can read the link above for my explanation why. Basically, itâ€™s because HTTP/2 makes concatenation unnecessary and also that not all CSS/JS should load in one file.
If you plan to combine CSS/JS, itâ€™s best IMO to do it only through your theme CSS options. (Of course, it only combines theme-related CSS and not plugins.)
70. Combining CSS/JS for big sites (ADV, MED)
I already said why not to combine CSS/JS, and I still stand by that. But I know some people are going to insist on it anyway because they care more about page scores or what other people on the internet saidâ€¦fine, do it like this:
EASY â€“ use the CSS/JS combine options in your cache plugin. Test your site. If some styling or functions break, then exclude the problematic ones.ADVANCED â€“ use a specialized CSS/JS combination plugin (Autoptimize is the best) alongside a cache plugin. This method requires more configuration but gives you more granular control over the optimizations and takes load off your caching mechanism. Can actually be nice since content changes wonâ€™t purge your CSS/JS.NOTE: donâ€™t use the combination features in your cache plugin if youâ€™re doing it with another plugin. Duh!NOTE #2: if your theme/pagebuilder has combine options as wellâ€¦yes, you can use them all together. But combine the pagebuilder and plugins first and then do it overall from your cache plugin.
What to do when styling or functions break (which will happen for 95% of you). Disable the optimizations and re-enable one at a time â€“ test each change. Do one with just CSS, then another with just JS. Sometimes, itâ€™s only one CSS or JS thatâ€™s causing the problem. Find out which one it is and exclude it from combining:
Isolation Method #1Â â€“ with combine CSS/JS on, open your site in Chrome > Developer Tools > Network (tab), and reload the page. Click the little red error circle to see which CSS/JS are missing. Exclude them and see if things work.Isolation Method #2Â â€“ disable combine (and also caching), and scan your site inÂ Pingdom. Sort the waterfall items by file-type (neatly displaying all CSS/JS). Now re-enable combine but manually exclude whichever CSS/JS you think is causing the issue. HINT: whateverâ€™s breaking is probably related to the problem. Did a certain plugin or theme function stop working? Try disablingÂ thoseÂ CSS/JS. Yes, it takes a lot of trial and error. It could be anywhere; maybe a plugin, maybe your theme.TIP: sick of trying to isolate the issue? How about combining only the CSS/JS for the single most bloated extension? For most people, this is either the theme or pagebuilder. So combine all the assets for one thing and exclude everything else. Itâ€™s an easy way to get most of the benefit youâ€™re looking for without the combine conflict issues.
What if youâ€™re still having issues? What if your site seems fast but has a small FOIT or FOUT issue? What if your site feels even slower? This is why I told you not to do it!
71. Manually combine custom CSS (INT-ADV, LOW)
Another clever way of reducing unnecessary CSS requests is to disable all custom CSS enqueued by plugins and manually adding them to your theme custom CSS area.Yesâ€¦if youâ€™re combining all CSS into your theme custom CSS, you probably wonâ€™t need those â€œAdd custom CSSâ€ plugins anymore. Get rid of them.
If youâ€™re lucky, some plugins have an easy checkbox to disable their CSS styling. Others you can only dequeue the CSS with filter code snippet placed into your functions.php. For plugins that donâ€™t allow either, you can manually edit out the CSS call from the plugin (but youâ€™ll have to re-do these hacks if you update the plugin).
72. Remove unused CSS styles (ADV, MED)
You can lighten your CSS by removing all unused styles. Simply go into your theme or plugin CSS and delete anything not used. Itâ€™s common to have themes and plugins with redundant/unnecessary styling for the same elements. Probably helps to make screenshots of your site page templates in desktop and mobile before you edit.
Unused sections.Unused blocks or elements.Unused buttons or icons.Unused tables.Unused typography.
One thing to note is that if youâ€™re removing from your theme or plugins default CSS, they might come back if you update your theme/plugin later.
Wishing for a methodical process?
The Tale of Removing Unused CSS from WordPress (WP Speed Matters) â€“ a great guide written by another respected WP speed addict. He also mentions all the tools I would have listed.Check all site templates on frontend. See which scripts they load. See which parts are obviously unused. Usually, there are many design elements of the theme/plugin that you never use. Start commenting styles out and then fully delete after a month if your site has no issues. Or make a backup and delete on the spot, up to you.
73. Remove unused JS scripts (ADV, MED)
Good luck trying to do this. Itâ€™s damn near impossible unless this JS was custom-written by you. The reason why many sites load unused JS is because itâ€™s loading JS for all the features available in your themes/plugins (yes, even the ones you donâ€™t use).
So sure, you can try to remove them manually but that means your theme or plugins might break if you change their settings or options later. There really isnâ€™t any way except to do a code-refactor and how the heck are you going to do that? Thatâ€™s the theme or plugin developerâ€™s job.
What we can do is perhaps diagnose your site and see how much unused JS there is. And with that, you can find where the bloat is in your theme and plugins and which ones to replace.
Find Unused JavaScript And CSS Code With The Coverage Tab In Chrome DevTools â€“ Google Tools for Developers
74. Manually refactor CSS/JS (ADV, LOW-MED)
If you got the skills, you can take it a step further by rewriting your entire CSS from scratch. Carefully cleaning and reorganizing the styles to make it easier to read and lighter to parse. In moments like this, you can even rethink your design to make things simpler.
75. Javascript async and defer (ADV, MED)
Thereâ€™s a lot of talk behind JS async/defer tactics, but they arenâ€™t always used for good reason. And it doesnâ€™t help when annoying page tests make generic recommendations for users who donâ€™t know how JS works.
Not all javascript should be async or deferred!Any JS used for ATF items should be left alone.Any JS not used for critical elements should be deferred if you donâ€™t need their functionality immediately.JS async can be used as long as you test first.
The problem with speed tests is that they try to improve page scores at all costs. They donâ€™t know what your JS is specifically used for so they make silly blanket suggestions that might actually hurt your page load!
Deferring JS will delay the visible effects or functions reliant on them!
AJAX (autofill) search functions â€“ defer is ok.Conversion tracking â€“ do you want to start tracking sooner or later? (I like later.)Chatbox â€“ for sales/support. Deferring makes sense.Content-rendering â€“ do you have special pages or content relying on JS? If that specific content is important or near the top of page, donâ€™t defer.Link plugins â€“ do you have specific JS for rendering affiliate links? I think defer is ok.Pop-ups â€“ defer is better.Security functions â€“ any JS that applies captcha or prevents right-clicking, or any other security. I think deferring is ok.Sliders or image animation â€“ terrible idea if theyâ€™re at the top of your site! Theyâ€™ll load slower if deferred! (Probably a good rule never to defer visible elements near the top of your page.)
Whatâ€™s even funnier for me is that you could just manually â€œdeferâ€ things yourself by putting the code in the footer instead of the header. Things like Google Analytics can be placed later and it will load later (after all HTML has been parsed). So if you really think about it, the only reason people use JS async/defer is to optimize the load for any JS automatically placed in the header. And if itâ€™s placed there, donâ€™t you think it probably means it should be loaded earlier???
So like I said, be careful what you async/defer! If you wanna play with it, test carefully. But in general, I prefer to leave them untouched to be safe. Thereâ€™s no point in scoring higher on a page test but your certain site elements or functions loads slower. JS makes little impact on well-coded sites.
76. How to minify HTML, CSS, JS (BEG, LOW)
Code minification decreases file sizes by removing all spaces and unnecessary code comments. This results in fewer bytes sent through the internet without any loss of function. Itâ€™s a win-win all around!
Small sites donâ€™t have much to benefit from minification.Larger sites will benefit more (especially for slower mobile visitors), but even then minification doesnâ€™t help much once your CSS/JS is browser-cached anyway!
My only issue is with how this code is minified.
Through a cache plugin â€“ ok for small sites.Through specific CSS/JS optimization plugin (Autoptimize) â€“ better option for large sites.Through a CDN â€“ best and easiest method, IMO.
Most people do it through a plugin, either cache plugin or one of those â€œperformance pluginsâ€ (Autoptimize) that specialize in combining and minifying your CSS/JS. The cache plugin is most convenient and works fine for all sites. But if your site is big with many pages, and/or lots of trafficâ€¦youâ€™ll get better results with a dedicated CSS/JS optimization plugin. They have more feature, more control, and best of allâ€¦they save you a lot of server load when you purge cache (since your cache plugin doesnâ€™t have to rebuild CSS/JS when page cache is rebuilt).
The extra load on cache prebuild is bad if you have a big site (and minifying with cache plugin). Every time cache purges, it completely rebuilds all pages and CSS/JS. Itâ€™s fast on a 10-20 page site but awful if you have many pages and different page layouts.The extra load can also be bad if you have low traffic (and no cache prebuild). Since uncached visits will take longer to load (thanks to the extra task of minification).
The easiest way to minify is enable it from your CDN (so it processes on their severs) instead of slowing down your web server.
I only enable minification from Cloudflare. I donâ€™t use it from any plugins.Enabling it is easy. Just check the boxes.
77. Lazy loading images (INT, LOW)
I hate lazyload as a general tactic. It makes your site appear faster to page tests, but loads images slower for human visitors. This is terrible UX! If youâ€™re going to use it, you have to know which things should be lazy loaded and which things should not.
It is SAFE to lazy load images below the fold but NOT if your site has many fast-scroll users (like shopping sites).It is NOT RECOMMENDED to lazy load any images at the top of the site (header, banner) obviously since that makes them appear slower to visitors.It is NOT NECESSARY to lazy load images if you donâ€™t have many or if theyâ€™re small.
In optimizing many sites every week, I can assure you that 99% of them would look faster without lazy load. It sucks that most sites canâ€™t control which images lazy load or not. Currently, itâ€™s either an ON or OFF setting in cache plugins. No granular access. Native lazy load is available in recent browsers through attributes to specify â€œlazyâ€ (on) or â€œeagerâ€ (off) or â€œautoâ€ (browser determines). But if you want to make it easy on yourself, I suggest not lazy-loading.
So lazy loading doesnâ€™t speed up page load? â€“ nope! It delays it. Your site only gets higher page scores because those donâ€™t trigger your images to load like real visitors will.But doesnâ€™t lazy loading decrease bandwidth use? â€“ yes but thatâ€™s not much benefit unless your images are huge or you have that many of them.Doesnâ€™t lazy loading help by loading fewer things? â€“ it doesnâ€™t load fewer. It loads the same but delays them. If your user doesnâ€™t scroll, it helps. If your user scrolls, it hurts.
78. Conditional CSS/JS asset loaders (ADV, LOW-MED)
There are several plugins out there (usually called â€œasset optimizersâ€, â€œasset organizersâ€, or â€œplugin organizersâ€) that can decide which pages will allow which CSS/JS to load. Some organize by plugin, disabling PLUGIN activation on the pages you choose. Others organize by CSS/JS, disabling CSS/JS load on the pages you choose.
They are a lot of work to configure and cause problems for your site if youâ€™re not careful. You also have to be careful which ones you choose. Some are written well. Others are terrible because their plugin adds its own load overhead, which defeats the purpose! If you insist on messing with these, research them for yourself and good luck.
Donâ€™t try to remove every little thing off every little page. Focus on the heavier plugins and CSS/JS.Focus on your slower pages and more important pages (like Home or Cart/Checkout).I like WP Gonzalez and Asset CleanUp. Generally, I recommend you not to use any of these plugins and to just pick lean plugins in the first place. I donâ€™t use these as I like to optimize manually.
79. Deploying a CDN aka â€œcontent delivery networkâ€ (INT, MED)
Do you need a CDN? If your traffic is localâ€”NO!Try Cloudflare for easiest free CDN. (Great for beginners and many sites.)Want better performance than Cloudflare? Try BunnyCDN (still low cost).Need CDN for large files? Try S3 and Cloudfront!Want a more aggressive â€œpush CDNâ€? Look it up!Some CDNs cover certain geographical areas better than others.
Network latency time is a common area of slowdown in delivering static assets (images, css, js). Faraway visitors have to wait 1-3 secs longer to receive requested assets. But if you use a CDN service, the files load faster since theyâ€™ll come from a mirror server closer to the visitor. Thatâ€™s all a CDN service really is, a company with multiple mirror servers all over the world. How they differ is in their pricing, features, and performance around the world.
If you donâ€™t know what youâ€™re doing, just get Cloudflare and be done with it. Itâ€™s free and works well enough. If you want to venture down the rabbit hole of CDNâ€™s. Just know that there are 2 kinds of CDNâ€™s:
Pull CDN â€“ the dominant method since itâ€™s less hassle for users. The first visitor loads the CDN (experiencing delayed page load) but all subsequent visitors get faster speeds. Sites with low traffic may feel itâ€™s not worth it, since CDN cache expires before next visitor arrives.Push CDN â€“ higher performance since files are manually â€œpushedâ€ to the CDNâ€™s mirror servers by you or your CDN management plugin. With push CDNâ€™s, no visitors will ever experience a â€œslow CDN pullâ€. Downside is itâ€™s more management to push files and things can break or look incorrect if visitors reach a site CDN missing updated files.
Traditional CDNâ€™s vs Cloudflare
Technically, Cloudflare is not a CDN but has CDN-like features. Itâ€™s actually a DNS service. You enable it by pointing your domain (from your registrar) to Cloudflareâ€™s nameservers. Then manage your DNS functions from Cloudflare, pointing it back to your webhost and enabling Cloudflareâ€™s performance/security features.Traditional CDNâ€™s work by supplying you with a domain zone (like â€œ123yourdomain.maxcdn.com) where your assets are mirrored. Then you configure your site to load all static assets from this zone. You can also mask that CDN domain behind yours (like â€œcdn.yourdomain.comâ€).Both traditional CDNâ€™s and Cloudflare can be managed by a CDN plugin on your site. You can also manage them from your cache plugin (most convenient). This way, your cache plugin purges both server cache and CDN cache at the same time.
80. Cloudflare optimization (INT, LOW-MED)
There are many little optimizations you can do with Cloudflare aside from just enabling a CDN. There are also some settings you shouldnâ€™t touch (because they potentially break your site or hurt performance). Please follow my guide:
Cloudflare settings guide (best performance)
Yes, I think you should use Cloudflare even if you donâ€™t want their performance/security features. You can use them only for DNS functions. Their proxy is easily disabled from the DNS tab; just turn all the orange clouds to grey.
81. Hosting videos locally vs externally (INT, HIGH)
Donâ€™t host videos from your server (especially if you need them to load fast) OR you have high traffic or large videos.CDN can help serve locally-loaded videos.Video hosts (Youtube, Vimeo) can make external-hosting cheaper.S3 or Vimeo are great for hosting private videos.
If your video is auto-played on page load, you need the fastest load possible. I donâ€™t recommend loading them from your server since that can quickly run up bandwidth limits and slow down your server.
CDN â€“ less technical work as your videos still sit on the server. CDN will serve the video quickly worldwide, but can get expensive if you have big videos and/or lots of traffic.Free video hosting (Youtube, Vimeo) â€“ low cost, integrates with video community, but loads slow external scripts. You can get around the external scripts using iframe-lazyload but that wonâ€™t help for auto-play videos.Paid external hosting (S3+Cloudfront, Vimeo business) â€“ costs money but gives you more control over how your videos look and also allows you to make them private, only viewable from your sites. (Good for members-only content.) Some services like Wistia, are really expensive but come with conversion-tracking features and other junk, hahaha.
Hosting videos elsewhere is always a great idea. The only issue is making sure they load fast enough and donâ€™t run up your bills. Storing them in S3 is handy if you like having control and flexibility over the videos.
S3 is great for integrating with other software, like ecommerce or download management, but requires more technical work and can costs money. S3 is good for video downloads and streaming, but can be slow for overseas users. Therefore, you should always integrate S3 with Cloudfront CDN!S3 and Cloudfront are both Amazon AWS, making them easy to integrate.
Vimeo paid plans are absolutely awesome; I love them, too. Easy to generate featured images (using plugins), easy to put into your content (it just embeds). Can control which domains it shows on. Comes with nice video reports, counting views, other user tracking.
My last note is that if this video is on your home page right at the topâ€¦itâ€™s probably worth testing different methods to see which one loads it the fastest. Maybe from your server, maybe S3 + Cloudfront, maybe Youtube/Vimeoâ€¦who knows, test it! All other non-essential videos, their slowdown is more because of the video player than the actual video itself. And for those, I have more tactics. ğŸ™‚
82. Hosting large files (INT, MED)
Just like with videos, you should not host large files on your server at all. Even if theyâ€™re seldom accessed or downloaded. Just one person downloading a 1gb file from your server is enough to slow down your regular web-traffic. Also, itâ€™s more sensible not to have giant files on the server when doing site backups (waste of space).
Use S3 to store the files.Combine it with Amazonâ€™s Cloudfront CDN feature if you need faster download speeds to visitors around the world.Large files for me is anything above 50mb. If you have just one 200mb that rarely gets downloaded, ok fine. If you have a 1gb file or many 200mb filesâ€¦probably not.Some servers are stronger than others, right?
83. Managing a large media library (INT, MED)
Some sites have such a massive media library (tons of images) that it no longer fits on the web-server. This is a performance issue because the web-servers disk is usually the fastest and most convenient place to retrieve website files. Putting your images anywhere else is likely to be slower retrieval.
You have a few choices in moments like this, each with pros & cons:
Upgrade the server plan â€“ easy way to get more space and better performance without changing your site much. But costs more and still might not be enough space.Offload to S3 â€“ using the fantastic WP Offload Media plugin. It allows Cloudfront CDN integration, too! I love this method but some people might not like the cost.Add block storage â€“ theoretically fast enough for application-use and also affordable ($1/month per 10gb) but I feel like itâ€™s messy and not all that flexible. Sure you can mount it to just some directories or even the entire wp-uploads directory.ORRR you can just delete unused media sizes if you want to quickly shrink your library. Iâ€™ve seen sites go from 100k to 10k images with no design changes!
Yes, there are alternative plugins that do what WP Offload Media does, but none of them with the same respect as its development team (Delicious Brains).
8. External asset optimization
Optimizing external assets is very difficult if not impossible. These are all the files that load from somewhere other than your web server (thus â€œexternal assetsâ€). This can be webfonts (Google fonts) or font icons (FontAwesome), images, JS scripts for Google Analytics, JS for conversion tracking (Facebook Pixel, Hotjar), JS script for affiliate (Amazon), JS library, JS script for Youtube (or Vimeo), embeds like Facebook box or Twitter, JS for social media share counts, and on and on and on.
The hardest part about this is that their servers arenâ€™t always the fastest (no duh, a free service is not gonna dedicate all server resources to you) and their files arenâ€™t always the lightest. You may have seen complaints from page tests about them not being browser cached for long enough, or being too big, etc. Whatever the case may be, you have little control over files that arenâ€™t loaded on your server!
So what can we do?
Load them locally.Load them early (aka â€œprefetchâ€).Load them late (aka â€œdeferâ€).
