94. DNS Prefetch (INT, LOW)
Enable DNS prefetch by putting prefetch tags in your header.Or do it through your cache plugin.But please donâ€™t install a performance plugin just for DNS prefetch.
A great tactic for speeding up external asset calls is to speed up their DNS wait times. What slows down external assets is usually the network latency time to send a request to the 3rd-party server. The file itself may be very small but the network time is what delays it. By putting a DNS prefetch to external domains, your server makes the HTTP request earlier during the site load so the asset loads quicker when itâ€™s needed.
Common URLs to prefetch:
Google fontsFacebook PixelOther social media networksChat scripts?Conversion scripts?
Donâ€™t know which URLs to prefetch?
Run a Pingdom speed test â€“ and look at the domains listed.Or to get a full list â€“ open up your browserâ€™s Developer Tools > Sources (tab).You should browse several pages of your site to make sure you get all the common ones.Only prefetch the root domain/subdomain, not the entire URL.Also not necessary to preload all domains that you see.Be careful of ad-related domains that change on each page load. (You shouldnâ€™t prefetch these.)
95. DNS preconnect (INT, LOW)
â€œPreconnectâ€ is the lesser known brother to â€œprefetchâ€. Arghhh, hereâ€™s comes an explanation:
preload â€“ preloads assets for the current page.prefetch â€“ preloads only the DNS call for the next page.preconnect â€“ preloads the DNS call, TLS negotiation and TCP handshakeâ€¦for the next page.
Preloading shouldnâ€™t be used as it can eat a lot of resources and doesnâ€™t make sense for WordPress unless you know exactly why some assets need to be loaded first (and canâ€™t be prioritized in other ways). Prefetch aka â€œDNS prefetchâ€ is a safe low-resource way to preload calls, and heavily supported by browsers. It conveniently establishes the DNS connection so assets coming from external domains will be downloaded quicker when requested.
Preconnect is like prefetch but does a little more (it establishes the TLS/TCP connection as well as the DNS) but isnâ€™t as popular for several reasons. One is because it wasnâ€™t supported by as many browsers. Another is because thereâ€™s a simultaneous connection limit in most browsers. Ultimately, you have to decide whatâ€™s most important to preconnect, and the rest can be
prefetched.
Limit preconnect only to priority connections.Some sites do preconnect before prefetch. Others do opposite but also prefetch the preconnect-ed ones. Some also put prefetch in the same tag as the preconnects.I probably wouldnâ€™t preconnect more than 4 domains. Prefetch, you can do as many as you want.I personally donâ€™t bother with preconnect. Only some very big sites do. TheÂ preconnectÂ andÂ dns-prefetchÂ resource hints â€“ Web Platform NewsDNS-Prefetch and Preconnect â€“ One, or Both? Fallback? â€“ Stack OverflowUsing Preload and Prefetch in Your HTML to Load Assets â€“ Alligator.io
